Course.WEBDESCRIPTION:
This course focuses on the essential knowledge and skills required to successfully work in a vocational educational learning environment. You will learn how to manage your OH&S responsibilities, discover how the VET sector operates, be able to unpack training packages to meet client needs and ensure your learning and assessment demonstrates inclusive practice.
Please Note: In order to successfully complete this qualification you will need to deliver training for a group of learners in your workplace. If you are not currently employed as a trainer we will ask you to either volunteer your services to a community organisation OR we will provide a simulated workplace on your behalf.
h2. Agenda
During this course the intention is that the following topics will be covered, but not necessarily in the order given. Due to the variable nature of Adult Education classes, parts of the curriculum may be adapted to suit the needs of the class.
Content:
* The VET Sector – an overview * Expectation of Trainer and Assessors in the VET sector * Meet clients’ needs with training packages * OH&S responsibilities and legislation * Your role in ensuring a safe and healthy learning environment * Identify hazards in the learning environment * Assess risks * Develop action plans and monitoring the learning environment * What is inclusivity? * Relevant legislation to support inclusivity * Resources to support inclusivity * Your role in practicing and promoting inclusivity * Work practices to support an inclusive culture
h2. Objectives
The intended Learning Outcomes for this course are as follows.
By the end of this course, students will be able to:
* Explain the components of Vocational Education & Training Sector (VET) * Discuss and identify relevant workplace standards or benchmarks * Identify and unpack the different parts of a training package in particular a unit of competency * Define and discuss the concept of inclusivity in a learning/assessment environment * Select appropriate solutions, which could assist with different inclusivity issues in a learning context * Identify the OH&S responsibilities of trainers and assessors * Complete an OH&S hazard/ risk assessment in a simulated environment
Any student attending an accredited course must present photo ID at their first class to receive their qualification.
PLS NOTE: All classes need a minimum number of students to go ahead. If your course does not have enough students it will be cancelled and you will be informed. ***Please be aware that you maybe be informed of a cancellation &/or change via SMS or E-mail.
Course.NAME: Training and Assessment: Environment Units

Course.WEBDESCRIPTION:
This accredited program is for those people who currently hold or wish to hold a general management position within an organisation. It comprises ten units of competency which are divided into five modules. The training is delivered over a six-month period and includes in-class assessment and a workplace project for each module. Modules can be completed in any order.
The topics are:
* Personal Effectiveness (Module 1) * Business Planning and Project Management (Module 2) * Workplace Safety (Module 3) * Essential Team Skills (Module 4) * Managing Improvement and Change in the Workplace (Module 5)
There are a total of nine training sessions delivered on weekdays from 9:00am – 5:00pm. In addition to the face-to-face training we estimate a requirement of approximately one hundred hours of independent study which incorporates preparation for in-class assessment and a work-based assessment for each module. Please see individual modules for details of course content.
A recognition pathway is also an option for people with experience. If this is of interest to you please contact Isma Ismail on (02) 8752 7588 for more information Other Information
You can enrol in each individual module (module fees indicated below) or you can enrol in the full certificate for $1,200 and receive a $150 discount. Below you will find the dates of each module for the whole year.
Enrolling in Individual Modules:
* When you enrol in each individual module you can choose to attend the training at a time which is convenient for you. Your work-based assignment for each module is due three months from the end of each module. The advantage of enrolling module by module is that you can take as long as you need to complete your learning.
Enrolling in the Full Certificate IV in Frontline Management:
* If you enrol in the full certificate you are required to attend all the training within a twelve-month period. Your work-based assignments for each module are due three months from the end of each module. The advantage of enrolling in the full qualification is that you are committed to completing your learning within a twelve month timeframe and you save $150. * When you enrol in the full certificate the college will automatically enrol you in the next instance of that module. Please consider whether you are in a position to attend all training days AND complete your work-based assignments within three months of completing your training. The work-based assignments will take approximately 100 hours of independent study. Please contact Customer Service on 8752 7555 or 8752 7588 if you wish to re-schedule your attendance.
Course.NAME: Certificate IV in Frontline Management

Take your quilt making to another level. Learn to break the rules using machine stitching to make sample of many techniques used in contemporary quilt making.

As you make a series of samples you will learn – colour selection, free motion machine sewing skills and embellishment.

h3. If this may cause you a problem, please call us to discuss further.
h3. Sewing Machines: Adult Education has sewing machines which you may use. However, many students prefer to bring their own. If you do bring your own could you please keep the following in mind: * Check your machine before class. * Please bring a machine you are familiar with! If you are borrowing a machine, make sure you know how to thread the machine, wind a bobbin and change the feet. Bring your manual if you can and all your attachments. If you have a table that extends your sewing space, you may find that helpful as well. * In general, sewing machines are like cars. They need regular maintenance. Before any machine class, please take your machine out, check that it has the correct feet, and that it’s working properly. If it hasn’t been serviced in the last two years, please have that done. * Your good experience in any sewing class depends on your machine being in its best condition.

Joan was a national heroine of France and is a saint of the Roman Catholic Church. She asserted that she had visions from God which told her to recover her homeland from English domination late in the Hundred Years' War. The uncrowned King Charles VII sent her to the siege at Orléans as part of a relief mission. She gained prominence when she overcame the light regard of veteran commanders and lifted the siege in only nine days. Several more swift victories led to Charles VII's coronation at Reims and settled the disputed succession to the throne.

He was born in the Long Island, New York town of Babylon, the son of vaudevillian Phil Roy (Philip Cohen). He would later say that his father "was never home — he was out looking to make other kids," and that his mother "brought him up all wrong." His mentor throughout the early years of his life was Christopher Drum, who coined the famous catchphrase, "I hate those damn flappers." As a teenager, he got his start writing jokes for standup comics; he became one himself at 19 under the name Jack Roy. He struggled financially for nine years, at one point performing as a singing waiter (he was fired), before giving up show business to take a job selling aluminum siding to support his wife and family. He later said that he was so little known then that, "When I quit, I was the only one who knew that I quit!" In the early 1960s he started down what would be a long road toward rehabilitating his career, still working as a salesman by day. He came to realize that what he lacked was an "image" — a well-defined on-stage persona that audiences could relate to and that would distinguish him from similar comics.

Lisa was born in Perth. Her artistic talent was apparent at an early age and by seventeen she had already held her first solo exhibition. While studying towards her Art Diploma in Perth in the 1960's she won two WA Art Awards. She now has a Bachelor in Contemporary Art and is currently studying her Masters in Drwaing. From the age of seventeen she has taught in art schools, Adult Education, primary and high schools.

Salvador is the father of Surrealism.
Widely considered to be greatly imaginative, Dalí had an affinity for doing unusual things to draw attention to himself. This sometimes irked those who loved his art as much as it annoyed his critics, since his eccentric manner sometimes drew more public attention than his artwork. The purposefully sought notoriety led to broad public recognition and many purchases of his works by people from all walks of life.

Margaret Mead was raised near Doylestown, Pennsylvania by her university professor father and social-activist mother. She studied at DePauw University and graduated from Barnard College in 1923. She received her Ph.D. from Columbia University in 1929. Mead set out in 1925 to do fieldwork in Polynesia. In 1926 she joined the American Museum of Natural History, New York City, as assistant curator, eventually serving as curator of ethnology from 1946 to 1969. During World War II Mead served as executive secretary of the National Research Council's Committee on Food Habits. In addition, she taught at Columbia University as adjunct professor starting in 1954. Following the example of her instructor Ruth Benedict, Mead concentrated her studies on problems of child rearing, personality, and culture. (Source: The Columbia Encyclopedia, Fifth Edition, 1993.) She held various positions in the American Association for the Advancement of Science, notably president in 1975 and chair of the executive committee of the board of directors in 1976.
Kylie Gills has a Bachelor of Science (computing) & has been teaching for 9 years.
Rodman was an American screenwriter, most famous for his science fiction anthology television series The Twilight Zone.

Tiny Tim already had something of a cult following around New York when he appeared in the film You Are What You Eat. This led to a booking on Rowan and Martin's Laugh-In, an American television comedy and variety show, which turned out to be his big break. Other appearances on the shows of Johnny Carson, Ed Sullivan, and Jackie Gleason followed, and he made a name for himself as a novelty performer. Apart from his extraordinarily high falsetto voice, his appearance—long curly hair, large nose, tall stature (he was six feet one inch), and his relatively tiny ukulele—helped him stand out from the crowd.

Node.NAME: St. Trinians College
Node.CONTENTS:
St. Trinians College has been serving the inner city area for over thirty years and is a non-profit incorporated organisation, partly funded by the NSW Board of Adult and Community Education (BACE).
We offer a wide range of day and evening courses. You must be 15 years old to join a class, but there is no upper limit.
We accept people from any suburb. The College has a voluntary Management Committee who are listed below.
h3. Mission Statement
To provide the people in the inner city region with equitable opportunities to access quality adult vocational and personal enrichment education.
h3. Quality Policy
St. Trinians College is an established Adult Education provider committed to giving customers quality training and service which meets or exceeds their expectations. The College adheres to the Standards of the Australian Quality Framework. Our objective is to maintain a quality system which will enable us to continuously monitor and improve our proceedures, programs and services. Commitment to quality is the responsibility of every member of the organisation.
